Jonathan Ross docked £1.4m and given final warning by BBC for Russell Brand radio prank
Jonathan Ross has been docked £1.4 million in pay and issued with a "final warning" by the BBC’s director-general, Mark Thompson, as punishment for the obscene phone calls made to Fawlty Towers actor Andrew Sachs on Russell Brand's radio show. Image 1 of 3	Jonathan Ross has been suspended by the BBC and Russell Brand has quit over their obscene phone calls to actor Andrew Sachs. Photo: EPA/PA	Image 1 of 3	Mark Thompson, the BBC's director-general, offered a personal apology to Andrew Sachs and his family Photo: Heathcliff O'Malley	Image 1 of 3	There is anger among BBC staff that Lesley Douglas has been forced to fall on her sword Photo: BBC	By Anita Singh and Nicole Martin
10:30PM GMT 30 Oct 2008
In an unprecedented move, the corporation announced it was to suspend its star presenter for 12 weeks, and he would not be paid his £16,000-a-day wages. But while Ross clung on to his record £18 million three-year contract, Lesley Douglas, the controller of Radio 2, was forced out of her job. Following an emergency meeting of the BBC Trust, Miss Douglas announced that she was resigning her post after four years, admitting that she was ultimately responsible for allowing the offending material to be broadcast. The Daily Telegraph understands that Mr Thompson and the trust were privately furious over Miss Douglas’s failure to contain the crisis. They also blamed her for failing to "manage the risk" that was Brand, who joined Ross in making the prank call to Mr Sachs. They were broadcast on Brand’s Saturday night Radio 2 programme on Oct 18. Related Articles
The woman who hired Russell Brand resigns
30 Oct 2008
BBC statement over Russell Brand show
30 Oct 2008
How should the BBC spend £18m?
30 Oct 2008
Radio 2 controller's resignation letter
30 Oct 2008
BBC's ploy to retain Ross won't work - good!
30 Oct 2008
VIDEO EMBED: Brand's apology
30 Oct 2008
Mr Thompson finally took decisive action after a day of crisis meetings with the trust, bowing to mounting public and political pressure by suspending Ross from all broadcasting duties. His Saturday morning Radio 2 show and his two BBC1 programmes – Friday Night With Jonathan Ross and Film 2008 – will be removed from the schedules. "I believe in this case Jonathan absolutely overstepped the mark," Mr Thompson said. "It doesn’t mean in the future that Jonathan can’t continue his broadcasting for the BBC. But I have to say, I think he and everyone else should regard this as a final warning."
His comments leave a question mark over whether Ross will return after his three-month hiatus. The 47-year-old presenter has made innuendo and risque humour his trademark, and the fear of further censure could lead him to walk away from the corporation. The director-general added: "The ultimate editorial responsibility for BBC programmes lies with producers and editorial managers. The consequences of errors of judgment are therefore more serious for managers. Nonetheless, Jonathan Ross’s contribution to this edition of the Russell Brand Show was utterly unacceptable and cannot be allowed to go uncensured or without sanction. "A 12-week suspension is an exceptional step, but I believe it is a proportionate response to Jonathan’s role in this unhappy affair. "Jonathan Ross has already made a comprehensive and unreserved personal apology to Andrew Sachs and his granddaughter. I believe that he fully understands the seriousness of what has happened."
He added: "We agree that nothing like this must ever happen again and that tight discipline will be required for the future."
The chairman of the BBC Trust, Sir Michael Lyons, ordered Mr Thompson back from his Mediterranean holiday to deal with the fallout, and is said to be incensed that the debacle has dragged on for days. The number of complaints received stands at more than 35,000. Sir Michael said: "The transmission of these comments via a BBC radio programme represents an abuse of the privilege given to the BBC to broadcast to its audiences."
The trust has demanded that the BBC management broadcast an apology to licence fee payers on Radio 2 for what it called "serious and deliberate breaches" of the editorial code. It has also instructed Mr Thompson to write a personal apology to Mr Sachs and his granddaughter, Georgina Baillie, for the "deplorable intrusion". In their calls, Ross and Brand left a series of lewd messages on Mr Sachs’s answering machine, claiming that Brand had slept with Miss Baillie. Brand announced on Wednesday that he was quitting his £200,000-a-year show, and Miss Douglas followed yesterday. In her resignation letter to Mr Thompson, Miss Douglas said she took the decision to step down "with enormous regret" but stressed: "This is my decision alone."
She wrote: "The events of the last two weeks happened on my watch. I believe it is right to take responsibility for what has happened. It is a matter of the greatest possible sadness to me that a programme on my network has been the cause of such a controversy." She offered a personal apology to Mr Sachs and his family. Her resignation comes 12 months after the BBC1 controller, Peter Fincham, was forced from his job over "Queengate", in which a trailer was wrongly edited as if to show the Queen walking out of a photoshoot "in a huff". Critics said the BBC’s slow response to the Ross row showed that the regulatory system, overhauled in the wake of the Hutton inquiry and fakery row, remains flawed. Ross was unavailable for comment. Celebrity news
