British climber falls 2,000ft to his death A British climber fell to his death in New Zealand after telling his family he was “living the dream”.
Robert Buckley had told his family he was "living the dream" Photo: FACEBOOK	By Rosa Silverman
4:35PM BST 16 Sep 2013
Follow Robert Buckley, 31, tumbled about 2,000 feet while climbing to a small hut on Mount Sefton in the Aoraki-Mt Cook National Park in snowy and icy conditions on Saturday. He was wearing crampons but was inexperienced and insufficiently equipped, police said. Mr Buckley, who was originally from Southend-on-Sea in Essex, lived in Christchurch and had spent three years travelling the world. He was with three climbers from Britain and Ireland when he fell after slipping on ice. His body was recovered by a team of rescuers yesterday afternoon after attempts to do so on Saturday were unsuccessful. Related Articles
British climber feared dead after scaling moutain in Peru alone
03 Aug 2013
Climber dangles from crane
04 Jun 2013
British climber becomes first blind man to conquer 3,000ft rock face
09 Jul 2013
His mother Jill Ray, 58, described him as a “loving son and brother” and said the family was “devastated” by his death. She had been looking forward to seeing him at Christmas, when she was due to meet up with him in Thailand, she added. “He always used to say, ‘Mum, I’m living the dream,” she told the London Evening Standard. “He travelled so much and had hundreds of friends around the world.”
Mr Buckley leaves behind his younger sister Kate, 23, and brother Alex, 28, as well. His father died unexpectedly last year. Kate posted a string of kisses on his Facebook page today, while friends also paid tribute to him on the site. John Cruikshank, who attended Shoeburyness High School with Mr Buckley, wrote: “Wish I had half the get up and go of Rob, 100% lived his life to its full x.”
Another school friend, Sam Bundock, wrote: “Top bloke may not be travelling this world but def is somewhere else now be missed mate.”
The other climbers Mr Buckley was with were rescued yesterday after spending the night on the mountain. They were released after an examination by medical staff. Police inspector Dave Gaskin said: "There was a lot of snow and ice in very steep conditions. "It appears as if the party were insufficiently equipped and inexperienced for the climb they had undertaken." Mr Buckley's death came a day after 36-year-old Duncan Rait died after slipping and falling about 200 feet from a ridge in the same national park. The New Zealand-born man, who lived in Australia, had been dropped off by helicopter and was walking to a hut when he fell in the Tasman Glacier area. Mr Gaskin said the deaths were a reminder that climbers needed to use extreme caution. “I can’t speak for the first death, but in this case it looks like to be a lack of experience," he said. New Zealand
