FA chairman David Bernstein ready to deal with football's 'bad guys' and invoke spirit of 2012
From Fabio Capello’s departure to Roy Hodgson’s appointment, Luis Suárez’s ban to John Terry’s current charge, many of the Football Association’s most momentous events in the past year must be seen through the prism of David Bernstein’s moral crusade. Clean sweep with a new broom: FA chairman David Bernstein with England manager Roy Hodgson Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By Henry Winter
6:30AM BST 25 Sep 2012
Follow A sheriff in a suit, the FA chairman has been determined to bring order to the Wild West of English football. Capello left because Bernstein did not want Terry to enjoy the honour of the England armband at a time when he was embroiled in a dispute over alleged racism. Hodgson was brought in for his footballing credentials and also because Bernstein trusts him. The disciplinary tribunal that found Suárez guilty was independent but echoed the desire for high standards in the age of Bernstein. There is always a feeling with the FA chairman of his wondering: ''How will this be viewed down at the golf club?’’ Related Articles
