Terry found himself caught in the perfect storm of a campaigning chairman, a public increasingly disenchanted with underachieving England footballers and the censorious shadow cast by the Olympics. London 2012 strengthened Bernstein’s evangelical zeal. As the new season opened, he urged players to improve their behaviour, cut out dissent to officials, moderate on-field language to each other and please, please try to be role models, drawing on the “sporting spirit we have seen at the Olympic Games”. Players have been warned. Bernstein’s mission statement is clear: behave, be responsible. When called to debate football governance by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee, Bernstein detailed where his priorities lay. As an accountant, he acknowledged the importance of sensible, sustainable financial planning for clubs and his own organisation. Determined to clean up the game, Bernstein also spoke of offering “moral leadership” and taking “the high ground”. In robust health, Bernstein reaches the FA statutory retirement age of 70 next May. Such is the admiration within football for Bernstein’s moral crusade that he will be given an extension, probably taking him until the end of the 2014 World Cup. It is no time to be leaving the FA with a 150th birthday to celebrate next year. More immediately, Bernstein will soon be involved in the official opening of St George’s Park, he has Dan Ashworth arriving from West Bromwich Albion to guide the elite technical reforms and he really enjoys Hodgson’s company. He could take Hodgson down the golf club and the members would love him. Bernstein is a man who genuinely wants to do good. Walking along the touchline at Villa Park before the FA Community Shield, he took particular pride in being applauded by the Manchester City fans. They remember his crucial work as their chairman, steering the club through difficult times. There are certain concerns with Bernstein’s stewardship. For someone so strong on principles and a committed family man, Bernstein was caught out badly by the Hillsborough Independent Panel’s report. The FA’s response was sluggish and inadequate, confirming long-established fears on Merseyside about the governing body. Initially, there was no apology from the organisation that cleared the game to go ahead in a stadium without a safety certificate. Eventually sensing the families’ understandable ire, Bernstein recorded an interview in which he emphasised the governing body was “deeply sorry this tragedy occurred at a stadium the FA selected’’. It was partly damage limitation, partly the reaction of a decent man who realised the FA had erred. Certain previous chairmen would not have responded. A further issue is that the pressing need for money to cope with Wembley, St George’s and grass-roots developments has seen the FA increasingly in thrall to broadcasters. The 5.15 pm FA Cup final kick-off tramples on tradition and mocks fans from the North reliant on trains. Bernstein is clearly a corporate man as well as a moral man. England
